:::summary
George Washington (1732–1799) was the commanding general of the Continental Army, the presiding officer of the Constitutional Convention, and the first President of the United States — a man of extraordinary character whose self-discipline, courage, and selfless devotion to republican ideals made the American experiment possible. Providence shaped him for his hour, and he rose to meet it.
:::

